The Masterpiece Market

Switching to the top lots by price and hammer ratio, we can see the beginni=
ngs of a =E2=80=9Cmasterpiece market.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s when buyers, =
who are agnostic about the economic cycle, respond to works that are percei=
ved to be the best of the best. Ertegun=E2=80=99s Magritte was universally =
acclaimed as one such work. Ed Ruscha=E2=80=99s Standard Station was anothe=
r, as was the Monet waterlilies that sold for a strong price. Had the work =
been signed and in pristine condition, it would have sold for a price much =
closer to the Magritte.

Christie=E2=80=99s tried to address the dearth of masterpieces coming to ma=
rket by creating a value proposition around works on paper by big names lik=
e Basquiat and Lichtenstein. It didn=E2=80=99t quite work out. The Basquiat=
 was bought at just below the $20 million estimate by Jose Mugrabi, who cam=
e
out for the evening sale. It was interesting to see him bid on=E2=80=94and =
win=E2=80=94Peter Brant=E2=80=99s consignment ( https://www.christies.com/e=
n/lot/lot-6508402?ldp_breadcrumb=3Dback&utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%2811%2F26%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2=
F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a ). Brant and Mugrabi have done a lot of business together over=
 the years. And this isn=E2=80=99t the first time we=E2=80=99ve seen one de=
fend an artist=E2=80=99s market against the other.

$(ad3_title) ( https://ad.doubleclick.net/ddm/trackclk/N1956727.4235865PUCK=
NEWS/B32797622.409127535;dc_trk_aid=3D600981946;dc_trk_cid=3D226429236;dc_l=
at=3D;dc_rdid=3D;tag_for_child_directed_treatment=3D;tfua=3D;ltd=3D;dc_tdv=
=3D1?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F26%2F24%29&utm_content=
=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Turning to works with the highest hammer ratio, a record price of $864,000 =
was set for Gertrude Abercrombie, on a work ( https://www.bonhams.com/aucti=
on/29521/lot/1A/gertrude-abercrombie-1909-1977-silo-at-aledo-36-14-x-24-in-=
92-x-609-cm-painted-in-1953/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%=
2F26%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F17%2F24%29&utm_=
medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12=
a ) estimated at a mere $100,000, at Bonhams. Abercrombie is one of a group=
 of female surrealist painters whose work has become increasingly valuable =
in recent years. At Sotheby=E2=80=99s, three of her works, all quite small,=
 were sold for huge prices, ranging from $192,000 to $264,000. The remainin=
g works on the list
of lots with the most dynamic bidding were all estimated at $20,000 or belo=
w. The art market continues to trawl through the day sales for historic wor=
ks that are perceived to be undervalued. This season, John Ritchie, Emilio =
Baz Viaud, Raymond Barker, Herbert Bayer, Judith Rothschild, Alfredo Casta=
=C3=B1eda, Emmanuel Man=C3=A9-Katz, and John Opper were all in the spotligh=
t.

The top artists by market share were a familiar group in an unfamiliar orde=
r. Magritte was by far the most appealing artist, with more than 13 percent=
 of the dollars spent going to work by the Belgian surrealist. Ruscha was s=
econd, with 7.5 percent. The former market leaders, Claude Monet and Pablo =
Picasso, slid to third and fourth position. Alberto Giacometti and David Ho=
ckney followed. Roy Lichtenstein posted a strong showing with nearly 3 perc=
ent of spending. Basquiat came in just behind him. Joan
Mitchell, Fran=C3=A7ois-Xavier Lalanne, Willem de Kooning, and Wassily Kand=
insky rounded out the top 12.

$(image_link)

Finally, and perhaps most importantly, the bidding quintiles show that the =
very top of the market is regaining some dynamism. Works estimated from $40=
0,000 to $95 million had a hammer ratio of .94. Their average estimate was =
$2.9 million, and the average premium price was $3.3 million. So, if you=E2=
=80=99re in the market for a work of art in the low millions, expect to fac=
e some competition. In the $150,000=E2=80=93$400,000 estimate range, works =
were easier to come by. The hammer ratio was a weak .88, and the average es=
timate was $250,000 against a selling price averaging $273,000. So if you k=
new what you were doing and could recognize good value, there wasn=E2=80=99=
t much bidding against you in this price range.

Lower down, things got much more competitive. The middle bracket of estimat=
es, from $60,000 to $150,000, had a positive hammer ratio of 1.04. The
average estimate in this range was $87,000, and the average work sold for $=
112,000. In the middle-low price bracket, with estimates of $25,000 to $60,=
000, the hammer ratio was higher, at 1.24, which is quite competitive. The =
average work was estimated at $37,000 and sold at an average price of $57,0=
00. The bottom quintile saw the most bidding, with works estimated from $80=
0 to $25,000 seeing a blistering 1.41 hammer ratio. That means the average =
work estimated at $13,000 was likely to sell for an average price of $23,00=
0. Don=E2=80=99t let anyone tell you these buyers are =E2=80=9Cbottom feede=
rs.=E2=80=9D They are the health and vibrancy of the art market, proof that=
 there=E2=80=99s still plenty of appetite out there.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

That=E2=80=99s enough for today. I hope I=E2=80=99ve demonstrated that the =
overall health of the market is pretty robust, even if the big numbers are =
not there yet. In fact, these sales represent the first step toward the ret=
urn of those big numbers.

I=E2=80=99ve got at least one more really good story from last week to shar=
e with you. I=E2=80=99m hoping we=E2=80=99ll have the right place for it ne=
xt week. In the meantime, enjoy your Thanksgiving (for those of you in the =
United States, at least).

I=E2=80=99ll speak to you Sunday as we all prepare for Miami.

Yours,
M

